Introduction

This is an automatically generated report based around Mapping the SARS-CoV-2 spike glycoprotein-derived peptidome presented by HLA class II on dendritic cells. The raw data is accessed from PRIDE and the supplemental file mmc2.csv.

It simply takes each of the peptides listed in the file. Looks at the Scan it came from and then tries to access the raw data and do some basic analysis. This tests that the raw data can be loaded and accessed. A plot of the predicted fragmentation ions for the peptide is also shown. The plots are either standard from base R, tidyverse functions, come from protviz or are custom coded by the author.

The analysis is set up to use an RServer in a docker container and uses RMarkdown to generate the reports.

Analysis Overview

Often algorithms become complex from the need to work around hardware constraints. In many cases brute force calculation using all of the available data would take too long. Hardware improves over time and some of the short cuts may no longer be required. An example of ‘assumptions to revisit’ is in the protViz::de_novo function. Instead of calculating all of the possibilities it uses two approaches to reducing the data. We will explore these now.

The first simplification is to take the topN intensities from the MSMS data. This may become problematic as the data changes as hardware improves (and this is a problem with the data used in this study). On lower resolution equipment the topN intensities had a good chance of being synonymous to the topN peaks. As resolution increases, you may obtain multiple ‘top intensities’ from the same physical peak.

The second simplification uses a filter based on matching b and y ions. If a matching pair within a certain tolerance are not found then a peak could be rejected regardless of intensity.

After the filtering/data reduction step the algorithm proceeds to calculate the distances between all of the peaks and then looks to see if these distances match (with an error tolerance) the standard amino acid values. There is an issue with the algorithm in that there may be no entry for a peak at zero mZ. This means the algorithm, as implemented, cannot determine the amino acids at the start and end of a peptide sequence.

The protViz::de_novo algorithm, as implemented, was very fast on my hardware (single threaded) so there was a lot of scope to do more. We can handle a lot more peaks so the pre-filter rules were adjusted. The matching ‘mirror ion’ requirement was removed, the intensity filtering improved and an entry at 0 mZ forced in the distance calculations.

The testing is set up as follows;

  • Load in the peptide list and parse it
  • For each of the peptides
    • access the corresponding raw file and scan information
    • create several visualisations and apply the ‘de novo’ algorithm
    • Produce various plots and tables for review of the peptides/short amino sequences against those specified in the paper
  • Create summary tables and plot based on all of the MSMS data accessed (Appendix)

Currently we don’t attempt to call the full peptide sequence automatically or reject any matches (multiple matches for the same peak will be shown).

Alg V1 : protViz::de_novo

Really underwhelming results. Doesn’t get close to any of the peptides in the paper. The start and end amino acids are generally missing. The focus on amino acid masses results in the y ions being mirrored down so the left to right amino acids have the right to left overlaid massively reducing interpretability.

Alg V2 : protViz::de_novo with relaxed filtering rules, a lot more peaks and a forced mZ at zero

Results are better with the first and last amino often being correct. Little else consistent and multiple different aminos from the same peak.

Alg V3 : as Alg V2 but created a database of all of the unique b and y ions from the peptide sequences specified in the paper

Results are much better but not perfect. This is at first glance surprising as we have pre-specified all the fragment ions. May be worth looking into this at a later point. Could be down to differences in pre processing of the MSMS peaks.

There are examples where you can call the entire sequence from the paper using a combination of the b and y ions that are matched. They are not always the ‘most intense’ peaks and sometimes there are alternative matches that explain the data just as well.

In general this gets pretty good results.

Alg V4 : as Alg V3 but included short amino sequences. Brute force inclusion of all possible pairs and triples

Similar to Alg V3 except you can often build more confidence in which are the correct ion pairs from matching the short sequences and sometimes you can bridge gaps in the b and y ion matches.

Code profiling suggests the main time sync in the De Novo is repeated comparison to the dist table. Look at ways to speed this up.

As written, with a peak reduction down to around 250, the current single threaded code takes just under a minute to execute per MSMS trace with all the data loaded and the ion and peptide maps already created.

There is much scope for speeding up the algorithm:

  • Using more threads. A 10 to 15 times speed improvement should easily be obtained with multi-threading

  • Use alternative MSMS trace pre-processing to send a better initial set of peaks.

  • Map down the distance matrix to a sparse flat structure. The entries in the distance matrix (effectively two entries for each amino acid and combination of amino acids) is differenced and checked against an error threshold for every specified amino acid combination. Many possible remappings of the data could speed this up

  • The algorithm could be adjusted to use classification trees or hash maps to rapidly access all possible matches at a given mZ difference value rather than requiring every entry in the distance matrix

  • Certain calculations could be cached and reused (as long as the algorithm does not change)

  • Use the code profiler to highlight and then improve slow areas

  • Implement time critical sections in a faster, compiled language (such as C#, which is what the raw data reader is coded in)

Link ions and peptides and attempt to call the peptide

Currently the results of the analysis are diagnostic plots presenting the matched ions and amino acid combinations. No attempt is made to resolve conflicting information or construct a ‘best guess’ matching peptide sequence.

A next step would be to take the matching ions and attempt to construct some possible consistent peptide sequence interpretations.

Run the code on all/a subset of the MSMS traces not included in mmc2.csv

It feels a little bit like cheating to use the assigned peptides to attempt to de novo the sequence (but since we don’t get perfect results maybe no so much). It would be interesting to see what the algorithm produces on the many MSMS traces that do not produce peptides listed in mmc2.csv.

This is simple to do with a filter on precursor intensity or some alternate form of selection (e.g. precursor intensity and retention time).

It may be interesting to explore additional MSMS traces via raw data clustering etc.

Add functionality to collate unassigned masses

The diagnostic plots focus on showing ‘matches’. It may be informative to collate and analyse MSMS masses that do not get matched and look at adding additional amino acid sequences etc. to start to pull them out.

An extension to this would be to consider the creation of DIA maps for precursors that seem to crop up consistently but we have trouble defining a sequence for. Further replicates from the same sample may, in combination, provide additional information to call the sequence.

Robust PCA and similar raw processing on the MSMS traces

We need to explore how to map the mZ axis. Several thoughts come to mind:

  • interpolate to a selected common space (this was done to create the LCMS maps). This may distort the distinct intensity versus mZ relationships.
  • create a super-set i.e. every mZ observed across the MSMS traces is included and if not present in a trace it is set to zero
  • Look at the distinct masses that could theoretically be produced (in combination with the mass resolution) and remap/align all traces into a common space based on this.
  • We may want to look to charge state correction pre-processing too

After the alignment, things like robust PCA should capture inter-relationships such as ion pairs observed.

There are many possible peak detection algorithms to explore that would reduce and improve the peak lists.

Implement or call alternative free algorithms

  • Tutorial on de novo peptide sequencing using MS/MS mass spectrometry
  • Algorithms for the de novo sequencing of peptides from tandem mass spectra
  • Deep learning boosts sensitivity of mass spectrometry-based immunopeptidomics
  • Lutefisk

Diagnostic De Novo Peptide Plots

In the following per peptide sections of the report the same plots are used repeatedly. To save duplication an overview of the plots is given once in this section.

Parent MS

MS plot of parent

This is just a simple line plot. Once the MSMS is selected by using the scan entry from the mmc2.csv file the corresponding MS trace is found and a small section plotted around the precursor mass. The orange vertical line is the location of the precursorMass as specified in the index of the raw data file.

MSMS with theoretical matched b and y ions

MSMS protViz::peakplot of the peptide

From the R help page for protViz::peakplot :

peakplot labels a mass spectrum from a peptide sequence assignment by using the psm function with the appropriate fragment ion labels. Using peakplot it is possible to compute the fragment ion coverage and customize the fragmentation ions used for labeling.

From the R help page for protViz::psm :

The function computes a matching between a given peptide sequence and a given tandem mass spectrum (MS2). psm determines for each fragment ion mass peak the smallest mass error to a peak in the theretical spectrum from the peptide sequence. If the mass error is below the given fragmentIonError the match is considered a hit. psm returns a list of computed fragment ions and a vector of the mass error (Da and ppm). psm uses a generic ANSI-C function to determines the nearest mass peak of array of double values. If the plot is set to TRUE an error plot is drawn.

De Novo overlaid on fragment ion locations for peptide

The following three plots are multiple presentations of the same data. The latest de novo algorithm looks for matches for b ions, y ions and short amino acid combinations from one to three in length.

A y is prepended to the sequence to denote y ion matches. Similarly a b is appended for b ion matches.

Simplistic De Novo diagnostic plot.

This is a simple custom plot simply overlaying the ions from the peptide on the MSMS plot, showing the corresponding amino acid at the b ion locations and the plotting the ‘matches’ from the de novo analysis.

In this plot the sequence string is centred on the peak mZ in the x direction and at the peak intensity in the y direction. There can be multiple matches for the same peak. There is no attempt to make the labels clearer and they overplot. This gives an indication of multiple matches for the same peak.

Improved De Novo diagnostic plot.

This plot is essentially the same as the previous one except:

  • it is prettier
  • it shows the ion matches split by the sequence amino masses.
  • the solid dots show the most intense peak matched (or just the peak for ions) and the grey bar links to the second, less intense, peak (intensity2 in the table) showing the pair that matched the ‘mass difference’.

The plot y axis is in the original intensity space giving an overview of which matches are associated with higher intensities.

Improved ranked De Novo diagnostic plot.

This plot is essentially the same as the previous one except we are showing a ranked version of the y axis. The ranking comes from sorting by two factors; the first is peptide length and then all of the same length are ranked by intensity.

The horizontal lines show the transitions between peptides of different lengths and the small numer above the line on the left the number of peptides in the grouping.

Single amino acids also have the mZ value shown along with the amino acid.

A table with the raw values used in the plot (limited to the top 50 ranked) is provided after the plot.

Unique theoretical ion fragments from peptides

We take all of the peptides and calculate all of the theoretical b and y ions and then remove duplicates. These are then used in the ‘De Novo’ search for the peptides in the file. As mentioned previously, in theory, this should mean that we can find all of the peptide sequences but this may not happen due to MSMS pre-processing and additional heuristics used by Peaks or additional curration by the paper authors.

The 206 peptides from mmc2.csv result in 909 unique b ions and 875 unique y ions.

De Novo processing of selected MSMS spectra

Takes the peptides specified in the mmc2.csv file and the corresponding specified MSMS scan.

Tables have been created for b and y ions (see Appendix). All of the masses in the trace are compared to the ion maps and matched with an error tolerance of 0.01.

Amino acid masses in single, double and triple combinations have been placed into a look up table. A distance matrix of the difference of (reduced) MSMS peaks is created and used to find possible matches within the error tolerance.

The peptide sequence is not used in the De Novo algorithm calculations but may be plotted for reference.

Analysis paramters:

  • Mass error tolerance: 0.01
  • MSMS peak limit: 250
